@adehad Good point. IMHO when building a library you need to define where you put the criteria of what the library can do for the user and what not. So far, the current Jira Python bindings aim to mimic as much as possible the REST API and doing synchronous calls for that, at the HTTP level. There are plenty of situations where the current 1:1 python - REST API can be abstracted to give a better user experience, but that's not the current situation.

Still, the Jira REST API itself can be batched and already has asynchronous operations internally, like the UPM interface where you get a task id and then the user queries an specific endpoint with that task id to know the status of it. This can be abstracted on the python library again as a 1:1 with sync calls or put some logic above to do the task handling automatically for you, but that would require async code for sure and httpx seems like a good option there.

Now, for APIs that support batches, like searching issues by JQL, yielding them is enough and won't require much heavy change on the current code. At the end, the REST API that work with batches behaves like a generator already :)

